                          underling Build Procedure
                       =============================

0. Purpose
----------

The underling library provides simple, scalable means to manipulate
MPI-parallel, three dimensional pencil decompositions using FFTW.  Pencil
decompositions are a natural way to distribute O(n^3) data across O(n^2)
processors and are well-suited for memory-intensive, structured spectral
turbulence simulations and postprocessing codes.  It may be useful in other
domains as well.  The library is written in C99 and may be used by C89 or C++
applications.


1. Introduction
---------------

This document describes how to build underling from source code on Unix-like
systems.  underling uses the GNU autotools suite (autoconf, automake, and
libtool) for its build system.


2. Dependencies
---------------

The code depends upon the following:

    1) A C99 and C++ compiler from the same vendor (e.g. gcc/g++ or icc/icpc)
    2) A working MPI implementation (e.g. mpicc/mpicxx)
    3) FFTW 3.3 or later from http://www.fftw.org/ compiled with MPI support
       (--enable-mpi); threading support (--enable-openmp and/or
       --enable-threads) is also recommended.  The same MPI stack and compiler
       used to build FFTW should be used to build underling.

       WARNING: Intel MKL ships an FFTW3-compatible wrapper that does not
       faithfully implement the guru and MPI transpose APIs that underling
       requires.  When MKL is linked before FFTW, MKL silently intercepts
       these calls and returns NULL plans or missing symbols at runtime.
       Configuring a statically linked underling (--disable-shared) may
       allow greater link-time flexibility in applications that also link
       Intel MKL.
    4) GNU Make from http://www.gnu.org/software/make/

The following optional dependencies are recommended for full functionality:

    1) Boost from http://www.boost.org/ (>= 1.39, required to build the
       unit tests via Boost.Test and Boost.Program_options)
    2) GRVY from https://github.com/hpcsi/grvy (>= 0.27)
    3) Doxygen from https://www.doxygen.nl/ and Graphviz from
       https://graphviz.org/ to build the API documentation
    4) mpiP from http://mpip.sourceforge.net/ for lightweight, scalable
       MPI profiling (enabled with --with-mpiP)

On Ubuntu, most required and optional dependencies are available as system
packages.  Install the build toolchain:

    sudo apt install autoconf automake g++ libtool make pkg-config

Install MPI and the required libraries:

    sudo apt install \
        libopenmpi-dev openmpi-bin \
        libfftw3-dev libfftw3-mpi-dev \
        libboost-program-options-dev libboost-test-dev

Optionally, install additional tools:

    sudo apt install binutils-dev doxygen graphviz lcov


3. Configuration
----------------

If you have no `configure' script in the top level directory, run `bootstrap'
to create one using GNU autoconf and automake.  Using bootstrap will require a
recent version of autoconf, automake, libtool, and pkg-config's pkg.m4 macros.

Before compiling underling, you need to run the provided `configure' script.
Generally, just `./configure' will work, but you may wish to provide more
parameters.  Two useful options are `--prefix=DIR', which sets the top-level
installation directory, and `--with-grvy=DIR', which specifies a GRVY location
that was not autodetected.  Run `./configure --help' for details.

If underling's configure script cannot automatically detect the correct
compiler or MPI locations, set the $CC, $CXX, and $MPICC environment variables
prior to running configure.


4. Compilation
--------------

To compile underling after it has been configured, simply type `make'.  This
builds the underling library (static and dynamic versions), some examples, and
the underling_bench benchmarking utility.

    make
    make install


5. Testing
--------------

Automated tests can be compiled and run using `make check'.

Many of the tests require your MPI installation's `mpiexec' command to be
usable, which may not be the case on many high performance computing platform
login nodes.  The benchmarking tool, underling_bench, also provides a `--check'
option to confirm the library is running correctly on any scale problem.


6. Documentation
--------------

The full API documentation is generated with Doxygen.  After configuring, build
the HTML documentation with

    make docs

which writes the result to docs/html/index.html.  Building the documentation
requires Doxygen, and Graphviz is recommended for the generated diagrams.  When
a Doxygen installation is detected at configure time, the documentation is also
built as part of `make dist'.


